  "prompt": "If time slows down as you approach the speed of light, then what time scale is light on?",
  "response": "The concept of time slowing down as you approach the speed of light is a consequence of Einstein's theory of special relativity, specifically the phenomenon known as **time dilation**. From the perspective of an observer in a rest frame, a clock moving at a high velocity relative to them will appear to tick more slowly. However, light itself behaves in a unique way with respect to time:\n\n1. **Light\u2019s Perspective**: In the framework of special relativity, light (or anything traveling at the speed of light) does not experience time. From the perspective of a photon (a particle of light), its journey from the moment it is emitted to the moment it is absorbed is instantaneous, no matter how far it travels. This is because, at the speed of light, the time dilation factor becomes infinite, meaning that time effectively stops for the photon.\n\n2. **Observer\u2019s Perspective**: From the perspective of an observer in a rest frame, light appears to travel at its constant speed (approximately 299,792 kilometers per second in a vacuum) and takes a finite amount of time to travel between two points. However, the idea of a \"time scale\" for light itself is not meaningful because light does not have a rest frame or a clock that could measure its own passage of time.\n\nIn summary, light does not experience time in the way that objects with mass do. Its \"time scale\" is effectively zero, and its existence is instantaneous from its own frame of reference.",
